DDeessccrriippttiioonn
       The lltconfig utility is used to set up and  maintain  the
       configuration of the LLT protocol stack. It is responsible
       for managing the STREAMS plumbing between the LLT protocol
       driver and the network driver that it is connected to.

       lltconfig reads the clustertab file to determine the local
       node  number  and  network  device,  links   the   drivers
       together,  and  then passes to LLT the node number for the
       local node and the node number and MAC address information
       for the peer nodes of the cluster.

OOppttiioonnss
       The  following  options  are  available with the lltconfig
       command: Cause LLT packets  to  be  encapsulated  in  IEEE
       802.3  with SNAP format.  Cause LLT packets to be encapsu-
       lated in Ethernet-II format.  Specify the  network  device
       on which to link the LLT protocol.  (eg /dev/net0) Specify
       an  alternate  configuration  file  to  use   instead   of
       /etc/clustertab.   Unconfigure  the  LLT protocol from the
       device.  Enable verbose output.  Configure LLT to  use  an
       alternate  SAP. The default is 0xCAFE.  Enable LLT warning
       messages to the console/syslog. LLT is normally silent and
       problems are indicated by statistical counters.  Configure
       LLT to use an alternate MTU. The default is  dependent  on
       the network device, and the alternate value may not exceed
       it.  Query or change the values of  the  protocol  timers.
       Permissible values for arg are query, heartbeat:nn, peeri-
       nact:nn, oos:nn, retrans:nn, and service:nn, where  nn  is
       the new value. The timers are the heartbeat, peer inactiv-
       ity, out-of-sequence, retransmit,  and  service  procedure
       timers,  respectively.  The  values  should not be changed
       haphazardly, or the protocol may fail to work.   Query  or
       change the values of the flow control limits.  Permissible
       values for arg are query, lowwater:nn,  highwater:nn,  and
       window:nn,  where  nn is the new value. The limits are the
       low water mark, high water mark, and window size,  respec-
       tively.  The  values should not be changed haphazardly, or
       the protocol may fail to work.

